        leftContent: "<b>Chapter 1: The Last Journey</b>\n\nThe evening sun sank behind the crowded city skyline, painting the sky in warm shades of amber and fading gold. She clutched her small handbag close to her chest as she hurried toward the bus stand, her heart quietly blooming with excitement.\n\nHome — a word that once meant nothing to her — now carried the fragrance of love, warmth, and belonging.\n\nThe bus was crowded, but she didn’t mind. She found a seat near the window and looked out — people rushing home from work, children tugging at parents’ hands, vendors closing stalls — everyone seemed to belong somewhere.\n\nShe rested her head lightly against the glass and imagined the hug she would soon melt into when she stepped through the door. Her mother’s voice rang in her mind: “Tu aa gayi beta?”\n\nShe didn’t know that fate had already changed its course. Some destinations do not reveal themselves until it is too late.",
        rightContent: "<b>Chapter 2: Silence After the Storm</b>\n\nThe bus never reached its destination.\n\nOne moment, there were voices, footsteps, metal rattling against the road… and the next, there was only darkness. She didn’t know when her screams had stopped. She didn’t know when her heartbeat had surrendered.\n\nThe world had faded out, not slowly, not gently — but violently, like a candle crushed under a merciless hand.\n\nAnd then… silence.\n\nNot the silence she knew — peaceful or restful — but a hollow, starless silence that pressed against her chest like thick smoke. She tried to breathe, to move, but her body was gone. Only her consciousness remained, suspended in emptiness.\n\nSomewhere ahead, a distant glow appeared, faint at first, then brightening like dawn breaking inside darkness. She did not walk toward it; she was pulled.\n\nSlowly, the realization struck her — she was no longer among the living. Her last memory of Earth was suffering, and her first memory of the afterlife was emptiness.\n\nNothing felt heavier than that truth.\n"
