        leftContent: "<b>Chapter 3: Arrival at the Gates</b>\n\nThe glow ahead grew brighter, forming tall arches made of what seemed like glass and stardust. There was no door in the earthly sense, yet it felt like an entrance — a boundary between what had been and what would now be.\n\nShe stepped forward. The light beneath her feet shaped a path — soft, luminous, weightless. Other souls drifted in the distance, some peaceful, some lost, some wandering, carrying memories of their lives.\n\nShe remembered everything: her mother’s smile, her father’s funeral, the adoption papers, her dreams, her promises. Her grief had followed her even here.\n\nThen she felt it — a pull, gentle yet firm — guiding her deeper inside this strange realm. Not a voice, not a touch, just a knowing: She was being summoned.\n\nThe path widened into a corridor of radiant light, and for the first time since her death, her grief rose like a tide. She wasn’t afraid of death; she was afraid of injustice.\n\nSomewhere beyond this luminous silence, God was waiting.\n",
        rightContent: "<b>Chapter 4: The Daughter Who Wanted Answers</b>\n\nThe corridor widened into an open expanse, vast and empty. There were no jewels, no golden gates, no winged guardians — just boundless white stillness. At its center stood a presence: not a figure shaped like a man, nor a blinding light with a face, but something that felt alive, watching, aware.\n\nShe lifted her face — she had no physical eyes, yet she felt herself looking straight at Him. Not with courage, not with reverence, but with pain.\n\n“Why?” she whispered. “Why me?”\n\nTears she no longer physically had burned through her spirit. “I just… wanted to go home. I had dreams, I had promises, I had my mother waiting. I was orphaned once, and I accepted it. And then, when I finally found a family… you took that away too? What evil deed did I do to deserve this? Why does she still suffer while the ones who killed me roam freely?”\n\nThe presence remained still, infinite, wordless. Silence — heavier than any punishment — answered her questions with nothing.\n"
